1.1 Ridge Regression

We will use the glmnet package in order to perform the ridge regression and the lasso. The glmnet package must be downloaded the first time using install.packages(“glmnet”, repos = “http://cran.us.r-project.org”)

The main function in this package is glmnet(). For this function we must pass in an x matrix as well as a y vector:

x=model.matrix(Salary~.,Hitters)[,-1]# [,-1] removes intersept column
y=Hitters$Salary
head(x)# Returns the first or last parts of the model.matrix

We first fit a ridge regression model:

library(glmnet)
## Loading required package: Matrix
## Loading required package: foreach
## Loaded glmnet 2.0-13
grid=10^seq(10,-2,length=100)#implement the rigide regression over a grid of values
ridge.mod=glmnet(x,y,alpha=0,lambda=grid)# If alpha=0 then a ridge regression model is fit

Split the samples into a training set and a test set in order to estimate the test error of ridge regression and the lasso:

set.seed(1)
train=sample(1:nrow(x),nrow(x)/2)#note 1
test =(- train)#Note 2
y.test = y [ test ]
#note1: sample takes a sample of the size nrow(x)/2 from the set {1,...,nrow(x)} 
#Note 2: we put in the test set indices that are not in the train set

We fit a ridge regression model on the training set, and evaluate its MSE on the test set, using λ = 4:

ridge.mod = glmnet(x[train,],y[train],alpha =0,lambda = grid)
ridge.pred = predict(ridge.mod,s =4,newx=x[test,])
mean((ridge.pred-y.test)^2)
## [1] 101186.3

Fitting a model using the mean of the training observations:

mean((mean(y[train])-y.test)^2)# computing the test set MSE
## [1] 193253.1

We get essentially the same result by fitting a ridge regression model with a very large value of λ:

ridge.pred=predict(ridge.mod,s=1e10,newx=x[test,])
mean((ridge.pred-y.test)^2)
## [1] 193253.1

Check whether there is any benefit to performing ridge regression with λ = 4 instead of just performing least squares regression:

ridge.pred=predict(ridge.mod,x=x[train,],y=y[train],s =0,newx=x[test,],exact=T)#Note 1
mean ((ridge.pred-y.test)^2)
## [1] 115899.1
#Note 1: In order for glmnet() to yield the exact least squares coefficients when λ = 0, we use the argument exact=T when calling the predict() function. Otherwise, the predict() function will interpolate over the grid of λ values used in fitting the glmnet() model, yielding approximate results.

Using cross-validation to choose the tuning parameter λ:

set.seed (1)
cv.out=cv.glmnet(x[train,],y[train],alpha =0)
plot(cv.out)

bestlam=cv.out$lambda.min
bestlam
## [1] 211.7416

The test MSE associated with λ=211.7416:

ridge.pred=predict(ridge.mod,s = bestlam,newx = x [test,])
mean((ridge.pred-y.test)^2)
## [1] 96012.47

We refit our ridge regression model on the full data set, using the value of λ chosen by cross-validation:

out=glmnet(x,y,alpha =0)
predict(out,type="coefficients",s = bestlam) [1:20,]# we examine the coefficient estimates
##  (Intercept)        AtBat         Hits        HmRun         Runs 
##   9.88487157   0.03143991   1.00882875   0.13927624   1.11320781

1.2 The Lasso

In order to fit a lasso model, we use the glmnet() function:

lasso.mod=glmnet(x[train,],y[train],alpha=1,lambda=grid)# we use the argument alpha=1 for lasso
plot (lasso.mod)# the coefficients plotted as function of l_1 norm

plot(lasso.mod,"lambda")# the coefficients plotted as function of log(lambda)

Cross-validation:

set.seed(1)
cv.out=cv.glmnet(x[train,],y[train],alpha=1)
plot(cv.out)

The associated test error:

bestlam = cv.out$lambda.min
lasso.pred=predict(lasso.mod,s = bestlam,newx=x[test,])
mean((lasso.pred-y.test)^2)
## [1] 100743.4

The ridge regression coefficients:

out=glmnet(x,y,alpha=1,lambda = grid)
lasso.coef=predict(out,type="coefficients",s=bestlam) [1:20 ,]
